Option 1: Open the Website Inside Your App

Use a WebView to display the page.

activity_main.xml

<WebView
    android:id="@+id/webView"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent" />

MainActivity.kt

package com.example.notesapp

import android.os.Bundle
import android.webkit.WebView
import android.webkit.WebViewClient
import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity

class MainActivity : AppCompatActivity() {

    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main)

        val webView = findViewById<WebView>(R.id.webView)

        webView.settings.javaScriptEnabled = true
        webView.webViewClient = WebViewClient()

        webView.loadUrl("https://www.w3schools.com/java/java_data_structures.asp")
    }
}

AndroidManifest.xml

<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.INTERNET"/>
Option 2: Create Your Own Notes App

Create Kotlin data classes and store your own summaries.

data class Note(
    val title: String,
    val description: String
)

Example:

val notes = listOf(
    Note(
        "ArrayList",
        "ArrayList is a resizable array that stores elements dynamically."
    ),
    Note(
        "LinkedList",
        "LinkedList stores elements as nodes connected by links."
    ),
    Note(
        "HashMap",
        "HashMap stores data in key-value pairs."
    )
)

Display these notes using a RecyclerView.

Recommended Structure for a Notes App
MainActivity
│
├── RecyclerView
│    ├── ArrayList Note
│    ├── LinkedList Note
│    ├── HashMap Note
│    └── HashSet Note
│
└── DetailActivity
      └── Full Note

This approach is better for learning Android development because you'll practice:

RecyclerView
Adapters
Data Classes
Intents
Material Design
Room Database (later)

